ckers or malware, or government-mandated regulation may reduce confidence in the EZ365 Platform and result in greater volatility in the price.</li><li>xv. Political or economic crises may motivate large-scale sales of EZ365, which could result in a reduction in the price and adversely affect the value of EZ365. Digital assets such as EZ365, which are relatively new, are subject to supply and demand forces based upon the desirability of an alternative, decentralized means of transacting, and it is unclear how such supply and demand will be impacted by geopolitical events. Large volume sales of EZ365 would result in a reduction in its price.</li><li>xvi. It is possible that a digital asset other than EZ365 could have features that make it more desirable to a material portion of the digital asset user base, resulting in a reduction in demand for EZ365, which could have a negative impact on the use and price of EZ365. It is possible that a comparable product could become materially popular due to either a perceived or exposed shortcoming of the EZ365 Platform that is not immediately addressed by the EZ365 Team, or a perceived advantage of a comparable product that includes features not incorporated into the EZ365 Platform. If this product obtains significant market share, it could have a negative impact on the demand for, and price of, EZ365.</li><li>xvii. EZ365 transactions are irrevocable and stolen or incorrectly transferred EZ365 may be irretrievable. As a result, any incorrectly executed EZ365 transactions could materially and adversely affect the value of EZ365. Cryptocurrency transactions are not, from an administrative perspective, reversible without the consent and active participation of the recipient of the transaction or, in theory, control or consent of a majority of the processing power on the host blockchain platform. Once a transaction has been verified and recorded in a block that is added to the blockchain, an incorrect transfer of EZ365 or a theft of 